  "prompt": "What is the best way to simplify [math]\\frac{x-\\frac{1}{x}}{1+\\frac{1}{x}}[/math] where defined?",
  "response": "To simplify the expression \\(\\frac{x - \\frac{1}{x}}{1 + \\frac{1}{x}}\\), we'll follow these steps:\n\n1. **Find a common denominator for the numerator and the denominator:**\n   \\[\n   \\frac{x - \\frac{1}{x}}{1 + \\frac{1}{x}} = \\frac{\\frac{x^2 - 1}{x}}{\\frac{x + 1}{x}}\n   \\]\n\n2. **Simplify the complex fraction by multiplying the numerator by the reciprocal of the denominator:**\n   \\[\n   \\frac{\\frac{x^2 - 1}{x}}{\\frac{x + 1}{x}} = \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x} \\cdot \\frac{x}{x + 1}\n   \\]\n\n3. **Cancel the common factor \\(x\\) in the numerator and the denominator:**\n   \\[\n   \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x} \\cdot \\frac{x}{x + 1} = \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x + 1}\n   \\]\n\n4. **Factor the numerator \\(x^2 - 1\\) as a difference of squares:**\n   \\[\n   x^2 - 1 = (x - 1)(x + 1)\n   \\]\n   So the expression becomes:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{(x - 1)(x + 1)}{x + 1}\n   \\]\n\n5. **Cancel the common factor \\(x + 1\\) in the numerator and the denominator:**\n   \\[\n   \\frac{(x - 1)(x + 1)}{x + 1} = x - 1\n   \\]\n\nTherefore, the simplified form of the expression \\(\\frac{x - \\frac{1}{x}}{1 + \\frac{1}{x}}\\) is \\(x - 1\\), where \\(x \\neq -1\\) and \\(x \\neq 0\\) (since division by zero is undefined).",
